eceives the (new) message of salvation. Crucial to making these more virtual forms of tradition appear plausible is the reconstruction of tradition's "truth-fathers"—God or the Buddha, as the case may be—so that they appear to endorse the legitimacy of these new ways of being traditional. Relying on a wide body of critical theory, this book presents an intriguing way to rethink key elements in Christian and Buddhist thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhismxDoctrines. 0aChristian art and symbolism. 0aDesirexReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aDesirexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aFetishism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Christianity. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845746840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438457468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438457468/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles